	<!ENTITY iof-construct "https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/">
	<!ENTITY iof-core "https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/core/Core/">
	<!ENTITY owl "http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#">
	<!ENTITY protege "http://protege.stanford.edu/plugins/owl/protege#">
	<!ENTITY rdf "http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#">
	<!ENTITY rdfs "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#">
	<!ENTITY skos "http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#">
	<!ENTITY terms "http://purl.org/dc/terms/">
	<!ENTITY xsd "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#">
]>
<rdf:RDF xml:base="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/biopharma/DesignOfExperiments/"
	xmlns:AnnotationVocabulary="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/core/meta/AnnotationVocabulary/"
	xmlns:bfo="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/"
	xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/"
	xmlns:doap="http://usefulinc.com/ns/doap#"
	xmlns:foaf="http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/"
	xmlns:iof-av="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/core/meta/iof-av/"
	xmlns:iof-construct="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/"
	xmlns:iof-core="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/core/Core/"
	xmlns:owl="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#"
	xmlns:protege="http://protege.stanford.edu/plugins/owl/protege#"
	xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#"
	xmlns:rdfs="http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#"
	xmlns:skos="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#"
	xmlns:terms="http://purl.org/dc/terms/"
	xmlns:xsd="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#">
	
	<owl:Ontology rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/biopharma/DesignOfExperiments/">
		<rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">design of experiments</rdfs:label>
		<terms:abstract>This module provides terms and relations for representing statistical models and analyses that quantify variation, effects, and quality across experimental, process development, testing, and historical data. It integrates core concepts from STATO within the IOF framework to support design of experiments, regression and variance analysis, response surface methodology, and statistical evaluation used for process characterization, monitoring, and validation.</terms:abstract>
		<terms:license>http://opensource.org/licenses/MIT</terms:license>
		<owl:imports rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/202501/biopharma/Statistics/"/>
		<owl:imports rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/core/Core/"/>
		<owl:versionIRI rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/202501/biopharma/DesignOfExperiments/"/>
		<iof-av:copyright>Copyright (c) 2025, 2026, Open Applications Group</iof-av:copyright>
		<iof-av:maturity rdf:resource="&iof-av;Provisional"/>
	</owl:Ontology>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="&iof-construct;AxialPoint">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="&iof-construct;DesignPoint"/>
		<rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">axial point</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>In a two-factor central composite design studying pH and temperature, the factorial levels for pH are 6.8 and 7.2 and for temperature are 35 °C and 37 °C. Runs performed at pH 6.6 and 7.4 extend beyond the factorial pH range and serve as axial points used to estimate quadratic effects for pH</skos:example>
		<iof-av:adaptedFrom>https://wolfson.huji.ac.il/purification/PDF/Others/GE_DOE_in_Protein_Production_and_Purification_Handbook.pdf and https://www.fda.gov/media/71535/download</iof-av:adaptedFrom>
		<iof-av:explanatoryNote>Axial points, also called star points, extend outward beyond the factorial cube in response-surface designs such as the central composite design. They are positioned at specified distances, often denoted α, beyond the high and low factorial levels. These additional runs enable estimation of quadratic terms and curvature effects that cannot be obtained from factorial and center points alone. Including axial points improves model accuracy, supports process optimization, and strengthens justification of the design space near the boundaries of the studied region.</iof-av:explanatoryNote>
		<iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en-US">design point where one factor is assigned a level outside the factorial range specified for that factor in the experimental design, enabling estimation of curvature in the response</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="&iof-construct;CenterPoint">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="&iof-construct;DesignPoint"/>
		<rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">center point</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>In a two-factor experiment where pH ranges from 6.8 to 7.2 and temperature from 35 °C to 37 °C, the condition at pH 7.0 and 36 °C is the center point.</skos:example>
		<iof-av:adaptedFrom>https://wolfson.huji.ac.il/purification/PDF/Others/GE_DOE_in_Protein_Production_and_Purification_Handbook.pdf and https://www.fda.gov/media/71535/download</iof-av:adaptedFrom>
		<iof-av:explanatoryNote>Center points are experimental conditions located at the midpoint of all factor ranges in a design. They are commonly included in factorial and response-surface designs to detect curvature in the response and to confirm process stability near nominal operating conditions. If the average response at the center differs significantly from that at the extremes, it indicates nonlinearity. Replicating center points provides an internal estimate of experimental error because identical runs are performed under the same conditions. Including center points improves the robustness and interpretability of a design and helps justify the adequacy of linear models and proposed design spaces.</iof-av:explanatoryNote>
		<iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en-US">design point where all factors are set at their middle levels, representing the central condition of the experimental space</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="&iof-construct;CornerPoint">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="&iof-construct;DesignPoint"/>
		<rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">corner point</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Three-factor factorial design investigates agitation speed (low = 100 rpm, high = 200 rpm), feed rate (low = 2 mL/min, high = 6 mL/min), and temperature (low = 35 °C, high = 37 °C). The eight unique combinations of these levels constitute the factorial corner points</skos:example>
		<iof-av:adaptedFrom>https://wolfson.huji.ac.il/purification/PDF/Others/GE_DOE_in_Protein_Production_and_Purification_Handbook.pdf and https://www.fda.gov/media/71535/download</iof-av:adaptedFrom>
		<iof-av:explanatoryNote>Corner points define the outer boundaries of a factorial design. They correspond to the combinations of factor levels where each factor is simultaneously set at either its lowest or highest tested value. These points provide the primary information for estimating main effects and interactions, since they represent the greatest contrast among experimental conditions.As described in ICH Q8 (R2), testing at these extreme combinations helps evaluate process robustness and ensures that conclusions are limited to the studied operating region.</iof-av:explanatoryNote>
		<iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en-US">design point where all factors are set at their extreme tested levels</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="&iof-construct;DesignPoint">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="&bfo;STATO_0000264"/>
		<rdfs:subClassOf>
			<owl:Restriction>
				<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="&bfo;IAO_0000219"/>
				<owl:allValuesFrom>
					<owl:Class>
						<owl:intersectionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="&bfo;IAO_0000104">
							</rdf:Description>
							<owl:Restriction>
								<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="&bfo;BFO_0000177"/>
								<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="&bfo;OBI_0500000"/>
							</owl:Restriction>
						</owl:intersectionOf>
					</owl:Class>
				</owl:allValuesFrom>
			</owl:Restriction>
		</rdfs:subClassOf>
		<rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">design point</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>In a two-factor factorial design where temperature is set at 35 °C or 37 °C and pH at 6.8 or 7.2, each unique combination (for example, 35 °C × 6.8 pH) is a design point. Running the process under these four conditions constitutes covering all the factorial design points</skos:example>
		<iof-av:adaptedFrom>https://wolfson.huji.ac.il/purification/PDF/Others/GE_DOE_in_Protein_Production_and_Purification_Handbook.pdf and https://www.fda.gov/media/71535/download</iof-av:adaptedFrom>
		<iof-av:counterExample>Randomly adjusting pH between 6.5 and 7.5 without a predefined plan does not create design points, since the conditions are not predetermined by a structured experimental design.</iof-av:counterExample>
		<iof-av:explanatoryNote>Design points represent the specific combinations of process factors at which experimental runs are performed. They are selected according to the chosen experimental design, such as factorial, central composite, or Box–Behnken, and together form the framework for exploring the experimental space. As described in ICH Q8 (R2), each combination of factor levels corresponds to a design point that enables systematic study of main effects, interactions, and curvature. The inclusion of corner, center, and axial points allows characterization of the response surface, while replication adds statistical confidence. The efficiency and interpretability of a design of experiments (DoE) study depend on selecting a balanced set of design points that provide informative coverage of the factor space while minimizing unnecessary runs.</iof-av:explanatoryNote>
		<iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en-US">factor level combination that denotes a unique experimental condition within a study design</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="&iof-construct;EdgePoint">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="&iof-construct;DesignPoint"/>
		<rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">edge point</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>In a formulation optimization study, excipient concentration is fixed at 50 % of its range, while temperature and humidity are placed at their high and low values.</skos:example>
		<iof-av:adaptedFrom>https://wolfson.huji.ac.il/purification/PDF/Others/GE_DOE_in_Protein_Production_and_Purification_Handbook.pdf and https://www.fda.gov/media/71535/download</iof-av:adaptedFrom>
		<iof-av:explanatoryNote>Edge points occupy positions along the edges of the design cube, between the center and corner points. They are used in response-surface and Box–Behnken designs to capture information about factor interactions without requiring all extreme combinations. By fixing one factor at its midpoint and varying others at their extremes, edge points improve model efficiency and help balance detection of interaction effects with economy of runs. Although ICH Q8 (R2) does not explicitly use the term “edge point,” its discussion of structured design of experiments implies inclusion of such intermediate conditions to assess robustness and interaction behavior within the studied region.</iof-av:explanatoryNote>
		<iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en-US">design point where one factor is set at its mid-level and the remaining factors are set at their extreme levels</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="&iof-construct;OneFactorAtATimeDesign">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="&bfo;OBI_0500000"/>
		<rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">one factor at a time design</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>A cell-culture study in which separate series of runs are performed to vary pH, temperature, and agitation rate individually; all other parameters remain fixed at the same baseline condition; A cell-culture study that first varies pH while keeping temperature and agitation constant; after selecting the optimal pH, temperature is varied in a subsequent series of runs</skos:example>
		<iof-av:abbreviation>OFAT design</iof-av:abbreviation>
		<iof-av:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/PROCO_0000275 and https://www.6sigma.us/six-sigma-in-focus/ofat-one-factor-at-a-time/ and https://www.itl.nist.gov/div898/handbook/pri/section2/pri212.htm</iof-av:adaptedFrom>
		<iof-av:counterExample>A screening experiment where pH and feed rate are both changed in each run according to a fractional factorial design matrix; A time-course experiment in which pH, temperature, and agitation are adjusted dynamically within a single run</iof-av:counterExample>
		<iof-av:explanatoryNote>1) The principle of an OFAT design is to vary one controlled factor through a sequence of levels while maintaining all other controlled factors at fixed baseline settings. That is, each experimental run corresponds to one experimental configuration that differs from the baseline only in the value assigned to the varied factor.
2) OFAT design structure allows identification of main (individual) effects but does not permit estimation of interactions between factors.
3) OFAT designs are typically applied in early-stage experimentation, screening, or process tuning, where resources are limited or interaction effects are assumed negligible.
4) Sequential OFAT approaches may update the baseline after identifying a favorable level for one factor and then proceed to vary another factor; the defining characteristic remains that only one factor changes per experimental sequence.</iof-av:explanatoryNote>
		<iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en-US">study design involving the testing of factors, or causes, one at a time instead of multiple factors simultaneously</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="&iof-construct;StudyDesignObjective">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="&bfo;IAO_0000005"/>
		<rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">study design objective</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>objective to determine which process parameters significantly influence product yield</skos:example>
		<iof-av:explanatoryNote>A study design objective defines what the study is intended to accomplish, such as identifying influential factors, determining optimal conditions, or verifying process robustness. It provides the rationale for selecting the design type, factors, ranges, and responses, ensuring that the experimental structure aligns with the intended analytical or process-development goal.</iof-av:explanatoryNote>
		<iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en-US">objective specification that prescribes the purpose of a study design in relation to  its declared independent and dependent variables</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="&iof-construct;StudyDesignOptimizationObjective">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="&iof-construct;StudyDesignObjective"/>
		<rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">study design optimization objective</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Determining the temperature and pH (independent variables) that maximize product yield and purity (dependent variables) in a capture step</skos:example>
		<iof-av:adaptedFrom>https://wolfson.huji.ac.il/purification/PDF/Others/GE_DOE_in_Protein_Production_and_Purification_Handbook.pdf</iof-av:adaptedFrom>
		<iof-av:explanatoryNote>Optimization objectives are used to estimate and model the quantitative relationship between significant independent variables and dependent variables. The goal is to find the factor settings that maximize or minimize the desired responses within the studied region. When multiple dependent variables are optimized simultaneously, trade-offs may be required. The predicted optimum is typically verified through confirmatory runs.</iof-av:explanatoryNote>
		<iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en-US">study design objective that prescribes determining the combination of independent variable values that produce the most desirable values of one or more dependent variables</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="&iof-construct;StudyDesignResolution">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="&bfo;IAO_0000027"/>
		<rdfs:subClassOf>
			<owl:Restriction>
				<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="&iof-core;describes"/>
				<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="&bfo;OBI_0500000"/>
			</owl:Restriction>
		</rdfs:subClassOf>
		<rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">study design resolution</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Study design resolution with the value IV describes a fractional factorial design in which main effects can be estimated separately from two-factor interactions but not all two-factor interactions can be distinguished from each other.</skos:example>
		<iof-av:adaptedFrom>https://wolfson.huji.ac.il/purification/PDF/Others/GE_DOE_in_Protein_Production_and_Purification_Handbook.pdf</iof-av:adaptedFrom>
		<iof-av:explanatoryNote>1) In design of experiments, the confounding structure is the pattern of overlap between model terms such as main effects and interaction effects that occurs when the design does not include enough runs to estimate all terms independently.Study design resolution summarizes how much of this overlap exists and therefore what types of effects can be interpreted without ambiguity. It depends on the number of factors, the number of runs, and how the experimental combinations are arranged. Higher-resolution designs reduce aliasing and allow more precise interpretation, while lower-resolution designs are useful for early screening with fewer experiments.
2) Study design resolution are typically depicted with Roman Numerals and three resolution levels are most commonly used:
Resolution III designs can estimate main (linear) effects but confound them with two-factor interactions.
Resolution IV designs separate main effects from two-factor interactions but may still confound two-factor interactions with each other.
Resolution V designs estimate both main effects and two-factor interactions independently.</iof-av:explanatoryNote>
		<iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en-US">data item that describes the degree to which a study design distinguishes different factor effects and interaction effects based on its confounding structure</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="&iof-construct;StudyDesignRobustnessTestingObjective">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="&iof-construct;StudyDesignObjective"/>
		<rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">study design robustness testing objective</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Testing whether small adjustments in buffer pH and flow rate (independent variables) meaningfully affect product yield (dependent variable).</skos:example>
		<iof-av:adaptedFrom>https://wolfson.huji.ac.il/purification/PDF/Others/GE_DOE_in_Protein_Production_and_Purification_Handbook.pdf</iof-av:adaptedFrom>
		<iof-av:explanatoryNote>Robustness testing objectives confirm that a process or system performs consistently within its intended operating ranges. They test the sensitivity of responses to small factor changes; if the responses remain within acceptable limits, the process is considered robust. Robustness studies provide assurance of reproducibility and tolerance to normal process variability.</iof-av:explanatoryNote>
		<iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en-US">study design objective that prescribes assessing whether small, deliberate variations in independent variables cause statistically significant changes in dependent variables</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="&iof-construct;StudyDesignScreeningObjective">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="&iof-construct;StudyDesignObjective"/>
		<rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">study design screening objective</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Identifying which buffer components significantly affect product purity in an affinity chromatography step.</skos:example>
		<iof-av:adaptedFrom>https://wolfson.huji.ac.il/purification/PDF/Others/GE_DOE_in_Protein_Production_and_Purification_Handbook.pdf</iof-av:adaptedFrom>
		<iof-av:explanatoryNote>Screening objectives are used in the early stages of experimentation to determine which factors among many candidates influence the response most strongly. The results guide subsequent optimization studies that focus on a reduced set of critical factors or conditions. Screening supports efficient resource use and ensures that relevant process variables are not overlooked.</iof-av:explanatoryNote>
		<iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en-US">study design objective that prescribes identifying which independent variables have a statistically significant impact on one or more dependent variables</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>

</rdf:RDF>